Outbreak statistics
Species / Apparent morbidity rate / Apparent mortality rate /
Apparent case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Swine / 4.38 percent / 3.60 percent / 82.21 percent / 11.52 percent
Wild species / ** / ** / 100 percent / **

* Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction,
and/or slaughter
** Not calculated because of missing information

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or
inconclusive. Circulation of the virus in the wild animals

Control measures [see comment]
Measures applied
- quarantine
- movement control inside the country
- screening
- vaccination prohibited
- no treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied
- stamping out
- disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s)

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Federal Scientific Institution, All-Russia
Scientific Institute of Veterinary Virology and Microbiology, Pokrov
(national laboratory)
Tests and results
Species / Test / Test date / Result
Swine / direct immunofluorescence (DIF) test / 10 Nov 2008 / positive
Swine / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 6 Nov 2008 / positive
Swine/ polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 10 Nov 2008 / positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[When subscribers download the ASF map available at the URL above,
they will certainly appreciate -- as we did -- the commendable, newly
introduced improvement in the WAHID interface, allowing the display
of information for domestic species or wild species or both. The
outbreak in domestic pigs in Krasnodar will display as a red circle
(key: continuing, domestic), while the case in a wild boar in
Ingushetia displays an orange triangular (key: continuing, wild);
please zoom-in.

The differentiation of outbreaks between domestic and wild species is
done in immediate notifications and follow-up report maps when
outbreaks are reported in both species and also in disease outbreak
maps. Users can now select wild species (yellow triangles) and/or
domestic species ("continuing outbreaks", red circles; "resolved
outbreaks", blue circles) and differentiate between the outbreaks of
events occurring in domestic and/or wild species. See also at the end
of the commentary below. - Mod.AS]

