Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Following its initial introduction into Georgia, probably through
the Black Sea Georgian harbour of Poti during the 1st quarter of
2007, ASF has been continuously spreading in the Caucasus region,
continuing its northwards march in southeast Europe. Initially
affecting the territories of Georgia, Abkhazia, Nagorno-Karabagh,
Armenia, and Azerbaijan, ASF penetrated Russia in November 2007. The
Russian epizootic has now completed its 1st year, during which it has
spread into and within the territories of Chechnya, North
Ossetia-Alania, Ingushetia, Orenburg (outside the Caucasus;
reportedly, wildlife affected), the Stavropolskiy Kray (Stavropol)
and, as reported in the notification to the OIE above, a 6th
administrative division of the Russian Federation, namely the
Krasnodarskiy Kray (Krasnodar). The total number of outbreaks
reported to the OIE by Russia since the start of its epizootic on 5
Nov 2007 has reached 45 as of 12 Nov 2008; see a summary, with a map
including all said outbreaks, at
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=event_summary&reportid=6546>.

Russia's declared policy addressing the control of ASF has undergone
evolutionary changes during the year (2008). The 1st and 2nd
follow-up reports, related to the Chechnya outbreaks, did not mention
applied or planned stamping out. The 3rd and 4th follow-up reports,
related to Ossetia, mentioned "modified stamping out" as a planned
(=future) control measure, informing about a limited number of
slaughtered animals but no animal culling. Follow-up reports 5-9,
related to the outbreaks in Ingushetia, Orenburg Stavropol, and
Krasnodar, mention "stamping out" as a planned control measure; no
stamping out is mentioned among the applied control measures. As
described in the current follow-up report 9, out of a total of 6798
susceptible animals 298 were infected, of which 245 died and 538 were
destroyed. It may be assumed that the 53 surviving infected pigs were
included among the destroyed animals; information on the selection
criteria of the other destroyed animals, and the compatibility of
this policy with the term "stamping out" (or rather "modified
stamping out" - see further), will be helpful.

OIE's definitions are:
"Stamping-out policy -- means carrying out under the authority of the
Veterinary Authority, on confirmation of a disease, the killing of
the animals which are affected and those suspected of being affected
in the herd and, where appropriate, those in other herds which have
been exposed to infection by direct animal to animal contact, or by
indirect contact of a kind likely to cause the transmission of the
causal pathogen. All susceptible animals, vaccinated or unvaccinated,
on an infected premises should be killed and their carcasses
destroyed by burning or burial, or by any other method which will
eliminate the spread of infection through the carcasses or products
of the animals killed. This policy should be accompanied by the
cleansing and disinfection procedures defined in the Terrestrial Code."

"Modified stamping-out policy should be used in communications to the
OIE whenever the above animal health measures are not implemented in
full and details of the modifications should be given."

To see the locations of the 7 ASF positive wild boars reported from 3
Russian territories in the Caucasus since the start of the Russian
epizootic, please go to
<http://www.oie.int/wahis/public.php?page=disease_outbreak_map>,
select African Swine fever, retain the period 1 Jan 2008-31 Dec 2008,
and zoom in to the Caucasus area.

A political/ethnic map of the Caucasus, including the mentioned
Russian and non-Russian territories, is available at
<http://www.colorado.edu/ibs/waroutcomes/pics/ethnicMap.jpg>. - Mod.AS]

